[[File:GeraldDM1205 228x390.jpg|thumb|right|200px|[[Gerald du Maurier]], who first portrayed Drummond on stage in 1921]]

===Stage===

McNeile and [[Gerald du Maurier]] adapted the first novel, ''Bulldog Drummond'' for the stage, where it was shown at [[Wyndham's Theatre]] during the 1921–22 season. du Maurier played the title role{{sfn|DelFattore|1988|p=224}} in a run of 428 performances.{{sfn|Treadwell|2001|p=23}} Du Maurier again played the role on 8 November 1932 in a special charity performance at the [[Adelphi Theatre|Royal Adelphi Theatre]] attended by King [[George VI]].{{sfn|Treadwell|2001|p=182}} The play also ran in New York during the same season, with [[A. E. Matthews]] as Drummond.{{sfn|Treadwell|2001|p=23}} McNeile also wrote ''The Way Out'', which was staged at the [[Harold Pinter Theatre|Comedy Theatre]], London in January 1930 with [[Ian Hunter (actor)|Ian Hunter]] as Drummond.{{sfn|DelFattore|1988|p=226}}{{sfn|Treadwell|2001|p=182}} A third Drummond play, ''Bulldog Drummond Hits Out'', was co-written by McNeile and Fairlie. It went on a tour of the UK in 1937 with [[Henry Edwards (actor)|Henry Edwards]] as Drummond, and opened on 21 December 1937 at the [[Savoy Theatre]], London, where it had a short run.{{sfn|DelFattore|1988|p=226}}{{sfn|Treadwell|2001|pp=26–27}} Fairlie later turned the storyline into the novel ''Bulldog Drummond on Dartmoor'', published in 1938.{{sfn|Treadwell|2001|pp=27–28}}

In 1974 the play ''[[Bullshot Crummond]]'', by Ron House, was staged with Alan Shearman as Crummond.{{sfn|Johns|1974|p=99}} The play was subsequently made into the 1983 film ''[[Bullshot (film)|Bullshot]]''.

